27:01.754 --> 27:03.722
before "Miami vice" before

27:03.723 --> 27:08.827
the Miami sound machine,
there was a Miami sound.

27:08.828 --> 27:11.429
The music, the original Miami

27:11.430 --> 27:14.432
sound we're talking about, came

27:14.433 --> 27:18.704
from this man, Willie
Clark and this space.

27:18.705 --> 27:22.140
What was this space originally?

27:22.141 --> 27:22.775
This was a little restaurant

27:22.776 --> 27:24.275
smaller than this and we were on

27:24.276 --> 27:26.077
the other side with
the record shop.

27:26.078 --> 27:31.616
Now it looks like a nondescript
barbecue joint, but

27:31.617 --> 27:36.521
back in 1963 it was the
home of deep city records.

27:36.522 --> 27:39.124
Willie Clark and his business

27:39.125 --> 27:44.930
partner Johnny Peersol
started deep city.

27:44.931 --> 27:47.532
The label became a showcase for

27:47.533 --> 27:51.903
artists like Betty Wright, frank

27:51.904 --> 27:58.209
Williams and the Rocketeers.

27:58.210 --> 28:02.380
It is a very, very long
list, an amazing list.

28:02.381 --> 28:04.482
It is about 1200.

28:04.483 --> 28:06.752
1200 songs.

28:06.753 --> 28:09.487
It just flows.

28:09.488 --> 28:10.889
I'm like a song mechanic.

28:10.890 --> 28:13.058
You bring it to me.

28:13.059 --> 28:14.625
I'll help you fix it.

28:14.626 --> 28:21.299
William and his writing partner
wrote such classics as

28:21.300 --> 28:27.005
"clean up woman" and
"rocking chair."

28:27.006 --> 28:29.574
50 years, 100 years from now,

28:29.575 --> 28:31.242
if you were to do an Internet

28:31.243 --> 28:32.677
search and punch in the Miami

28:32.678 --> 28:33.812
sound, your name is going to

28:33.813 --> 28:36.514
come up right away as principal

28:36.515 --> 28:38.116
creator of the Miami sound.

28:38.117 --> 28:39.317
What were the distinctive

28:39.318 --> 28:41.152
features of the music you were

28:41.153 --> 28:44.522
making that separated it from

28:44.523 --> 28:46.457
Motown, Philadelphia, New York?

28:46.458 --> 28:52.964
The culture was a mixture of

28:52.965 --> 28:54.632
Bahamian, Jamaican, and people

28:54.633 --> 28:58.970
came down from Georgia and
Alabama, but that Bahamian

28:58.971 --> 29:00.305
influence was dominant.

29:00.306 --> 29:01.140
Right.

29:01.141 --> 29:06.644
We would have bands who would

29:06.645 --> 29:08.780
march from Overtown all the way

29:08.781 --> 29:15.020
to Liberty city and
back in big parades.

29:15.021 --> 29:15.855
This influence, the dancing and

29:15.856 --> 29:22.127
the moving and the marching,

29:22.128 --> 29:22.728
that was the main difference.

29:22.729 --> 29:24.996
And you were teaching school
through a lot of this?

29:24.997 --> 29:27.398
Yeah, I was teaching.

29:27.399 --> 29:29.167
I would look around, put my sign

29:29.168 --> 29:31.169
in, and walk out the back door

29:31.170 --> 29:34.172
and go straight to the studio.

29:34.173 --> 29:36.842
But you know, the principal
knew what I was doing.

29:36.843 --> 29:37.543
Yep.

29:37.544 --> 29:44.883
I did most of the deep city
music using that technique.

29:44.884 --> 29:49.754
♪

29:49.755 --> 29:57.755
♪ If only I could fly I
